My new launch date has been set for Tuesday, May 19, with a backup on May 20! Launch window is from 7:35-11:30 p.m. EDT.
Happy to see the safe launch of Space Shuttle Atlantis.
No attempt tomorrow, my next attempt at achieving orbit will be ~May 19....I'll be in touch
sighhh launch scrubbed for tonight, I'll keep you posted on my next attempt.

@moonrangerlaura Thanks!  keeping my fingers crossed and knocking on wood.

T- 1 hour and COUNTING!
Been holding my breath for the last 45 minutes, but it looks like we are back on track.....problem fixed and weather good!
Countdown clock has been reset to T-50 minutes and holding.
Convective weather not an issue for launch window, cloud coverage worsens towards the end of window but should still be ok
Weather briefing in progress
Troubleshooting continues...
@N2GJ Certain cloud coverage is OK, we are still looking good for weather, another weather debrief will be occurring shortly
Testing to make sure issue is resolved satisfactorily, then they expect to reset clock to T-50
All boats are out of the hazard area

Powering down rocket to send small team back to the launch pad to fix a fiber connectivity issue
Clearing a boat from the area, should take about 20 minutes
Holding the clock at T-45 minutes. A launch support equipment issue is being worked.
Beginning to clear launch area.....
T-1 hour 30 minutes and counting. Surveillance aircraft out over the ocean scanning for boats that may be underneath flight path of rocket.
Latest news during Twitter maintenance: weather improving, 85% probability of acceptable weather for launch & shelter removed from rocket
Surveillance aircraft are in the air....doing a little better than yesterday
Only 1 cell in area, no lightning; mid-level clouds not as thick and starting to thin, 65% probability of acceptable weather for launch
Weather briefing in progress.....stay tuned.
T-3 hours and counting!
Launch vehicle, spacecraft and range are all green at this time.
New launch time of 7:35 p.m. This to take advantage of the expected better weather early in the window.
T-3 hrs 38 minutes

At T- 5 hours and counting for the launch of the Minotaur 1 rocket. Could launch as early as 7:30 p.m. EDT Window closes at 11 p.m. EDT
Just heard, next attempt tomorrow night...hoping third time's a charm

Tonight is not my night, a little more time on beautiful planet Earth
Plane has not departed. Another line of storms getting ready to come through the area....Ugggh!
T-1 hour and holding. Wallops is sending out a surveillance plane to check for boats.
Still T-1 hour 15 minutes and holding as the gantry is moved away from the rocket.
It's back on, lightning has passed and their rolling back the gantry/shelter at the launch pad!
T-1 hour 15 minutes and holding. Gantry is now back over the rocket.
Wallops expects a storm soon. They're moving the gantry back over rocket. Sky is still blue in the webcast http://sites.wff.nasa.gov/webcast
Range is now green! Severe weather predicted for tracking site in Coquina, N.C.
T-2 hours and counting!
Spacecraft and launch vehicle are working no issues and are green for launch, my favorite color!
T-3 hours and counting. Latest forecast shows 70% probability of acceptable weather for launch.  Conditions keep improving...YES!
T-4 hours, shelter roll completed, you can now see my Minotaur 1 rocket!
As the fog rolls in, Wallops is beginning the final process to prepare the Minotaur 1 rocket for launch.
Blue skies overhead - Wallops just issued a weather forecast with a 60% probablity of good weather for launch.
The launch webcast just started streaming again: http://sites.wff.nasa.gov/webcast/
Wallops issued a weather forecast with a 55% probablity of acceptable weather for launch. Glass is more than half full!
Wallops decided the next launch attempt will be Thursday, May 7 with a launch window of 8 p.m. to 11 p.m. Eastern, 5 p.m. to 8 p.m. Pacific.
Wallops has canceled tonight's launch attempt because of poor weather. A decision on the next launch attempt will be made later tonight.
@moonrangerlaura Thank you for your interest and good wishes!
Wallops continues the hold on the count for the launch. A weather briefing started at 7:30 p.m. Eastern, 4:30 p.m. Pacific.
Latter part of today's launch window looks the most promising, 10:30 to 11:00 PM Eastern, 7:30 - 8:00 PM Pacific
@NLSI Thank you for the well wishes NASA Lunar Sciences Institute
Going into a launch hold at T - 1 hour 45 minutes
T-2 hours and counting. Weather is still a problem. Briefing currently taking place. Stay tuned!
T-3 hours and counting. Weather still the big issue for the launch site Otherwise, the count has gone smoothly and no issues being worked.
Check me out in Popular Science  http://tinyurl.com/d6p7tv
The Coquina tracking station down range provides an alternative angle to look at the vehicle during flight.
T-4 hours & counting! Weather still an issue. Light rain in the Wallops area. The Conquina tracking site in N.C. is back up and operating.
Lightning around the Wallops tracking station on the Outer Banks North Carolina. They have had to temporarily shutdown part their systems.
The latest forecast from the Wallops shows an 85% probability of violating the launch weather constraints today. DARN! stay posted
It's Launch Day!!  Hoping the weather will cooperate this evening between 5 and 8 pm pacific time.

L=launch; launch date still holding for May 5, 2009
is L-15 days; Bling...did you know I'm gold plated, (gold's thermal emissivity helps me stay cooool)
is L-16 days.
My fluidics card has 48 sample wells ( 4 rows, 12 wells ea), each well holds 100 uL; each row has it's own reagent delivery capability.
is L-19 days.
Cell growth maintains a reduced environment while inhibition of growth maintains an oxidized environment; growth = red, no growth = blue.
Redox (short for reduction-oxidation reaction) describes chemical reactions in which atoms have their oxidation # (oxidation state) changed.
Reduction related to growth causes the Alamar blue REDOX indicator to change from the oxidized ( blue) form to the reduced ( red) form.
My experiment uses an Alamar Blue assay to monitor cell viability and growth.
My experiment is designed to measure the influence of microgravity upon yeast resistance to an antifungal agent
is L-21 days.

Next destination for me will be the Launch Pad 0B at the Mid-Atlantic Regional Spaceport. My team is back in California.

I'm leaving the hotel and heading to F7 at Wallops for my post-transport functional check-out.
